{
    "analysis": "The previous Executor step loaded metric.csv and trace.csv, aggregated by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and (cmdb_id, trace_name), computed global P95 per group over the full available series, and counted points inside the incident window (2020-05-29 02:00 to 02:30 Asia/Shanghai). From the returned aggregates: \n- metric.csv: almost all displayed KPI groups belong to cmdb_id=db_001 with many groups having 30 points inside the 02:00-02:30 window (full-minute coverage). Example KPIs: DbTime (P95=61.36), MEM_Used_Pct (P95=64.63), MEM_Used (P95≈246.8), LFSync_Per_Sec, Logic_Read_Per_Sec, Hang (=1), CPU_free_pct (P95≈99.36). Some KPIs have few total points (e.g., CPU_Used_Pct total_points=2). This indicates db_001 (a service-level component) is heavily represented in the window and is a primary metric candidate.\n- trace.csv: all displayed groups belong to cmdb_id=docker_001 with full coverage (30 points) in the window. Traces show interactions such as trace.from_os_022.remoteprocess.* and trace.self.*. Many trace error_rate series show global P95 = 0, and row_count/duration metrics are present. The presence of trace.from_os_022 suggests communication with node os_022 during the window.\n- Overall: metrics point to db_001 having many KPIs present during the window, traces show docker_001 capturing calls (including calls from os_022) with zero global error rates for many trace error metrics. At this stage we cannot yet identify which KPI(s) exceeded thresholds inside the window. The next atomic step is metric-level anomaly detection: find which (component-KPI) groups have points in the window that exceed their global thresholds (P95). This will narrow down faulty KPIs/components for downstream fault identification and trace-based localization.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name): compute the global P95 of value using the full series (do NOT filter by the incident window for threshold calculation). Then filter the group's points to the incident window 2020-05-29 02:00:00 to 2020-05-29 02:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai). For each group produce one row (limit to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points, points_in_window, global_P95_value, anomaly_count_in_window (count of points in-window with value > global_P95_value), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (the earliest timestamp of such a point, null if none), max_value_in_window. Also return the total number of metric anomaly points across all groups within the window (single scalar). Do not print full raw time series; only the requested aggregate table and the scalar." 
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor has computed global P95 thresholds per component-KPI over the full available series and counted how many points inside the incident window (2020-05-29 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 Asia/Shanghai) exceed those thresholds. The metric-level anomaly summary shows many component-KPI groups across node-level (os_*) and service-level (db_*) components with anomalies—each of these groups has a small number of anomaly points in-window (commonly 3) and there are 1,139 total anomaly points across metrics. Top anomalous groups include os_015 Incoming_network_traffic, db_001 MEM_real_util, db_005 MEM_Used, db_010 CPU_free_pct, db_013 ACS, and several disk/network KPIs on os_00x nodes. This narrows the search to a set of node and DB service candidates, but we do not yet know which anomalies form real faults (consecutive anomalous periods) or which are noise. According to the workflow, the next step is fault identification: convert point anomalies into consecutive anomalous sub-series (faults), filter out isolated spikes and weak threshold breaches, and rank candidate faults by duration and severity. From there we can localize root cause using traces and downstream logic.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Perform fault identification on metric.csv for the incident window 2020-05-29 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai) as follows:\n1) Recompute per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) the global P95 over the full series (if not already available). 2) Filter metric points to the incident window. 3) Mark a point as anomalous if value > global_P95 for that group. 4) For each group, find consecutive runs of anomalous points (consecutive in time ordering by timestamp). For each run (a candidate fault) produce one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp (earliest point of run), fault_end_timestamp (latest point of run), run_length_minutes (number of consecutive points), max_value_in_run, global_P95_value, breach_ratio = (max_value_in_run - global_P95_value) / max(1e-9, global_P95_value). 5) Filter runs to keep only those that meet either: run_length_minutes >= 2 OR breach_ratio >= 0.5 (i.e., >50% above P95). 6) Return a compact table limited to top 20 faults sorted by run_length_minutes desc, then breach_ratio desc, with the columns specified above. Also return: total_number_of_faults_identified (after filtering), number_of_unique_components_with_faults, and the earliest_fault_start_timestamp among identified faults. Do not return raw time series—only the aggregated fault table and the three scalars."
}

